There are different approaches to finding the longest common subsequence of two input strings, one of the classic and efficient algorithms is the algorithm of Knuth and Morris. It works by computing a set of column values representing the number of occurrences in the two input sequences of each column position. The longest common subsequence is then obtained by taking the value corresponding to the longest path starting from the bottom of the matrix. Here's a Python implementation of the algorithm:

```
def knuth_morris(s1, s2):
    n = len(s1)
    m = len(s2)
    max_v = 0
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(m):
            if s1[i] == s2[j]:
                max_v = max(max_v, 1 + knuth_morris(s1[:i], s2[:j]))

    return max_v
```

